<!-- ===============================================
     SECTION 2: WHY THIS AREA
================================================ -->
<section style="background:var(--color-base, #f2ead4); padding:80px 24px;">
  <div style="max-width:800px; margin:0 auto;">
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:0.75rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.15em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#b98229; margin-bottom:1rem;">Local Expertise</p>
    <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif); font-size:clamp(1.8rem, 3.5vw, 2.8rem); font-weight:400; font-variation-settings:'opsz' 32; line-height:1.2; color:#191817; margin-bottom:1.75rem;">The southern Brisbane suburb that families pursue for its large residential blocks, good school catchments, and a quiet street character that is increasingly difficult to find this close to the city centre.</h2>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      Macgregor sits approximately twelve kilometres south of the Brisbane CBD, sharing a postcode with Sunnybank and positioned in the southern residential corridor with practical motorway access and a residential character that families have consistently valued. The suburb is defined by its land sizes: blocks in Macgregor tend to run larger than the surrounding southern suburbs, and in a market where generous land content close to the city commands significant premiums, that distinction matters. Buyers who target Macgregor in 2026 have typically made a deliberate choice about the value that land represents and understand that this suburb offers an opportunity that comparably priced options in the corridor do not replicate.
    </p>
